.\outputs\codex_findings\full_audit_pass_11\codex_stderr.log:3507:outputs/sweep_r3_final/clinical/clinical_afib_anticoagulation/report.md:9:Most patients with non-valvular atrial fibrillation (AF) or acute venous thromboembolism (VTE) can be treated with a direct-acting oral anticoagulant (DOAC).[3] In contrast, warfarin is the first-line oral anticoagulant for valvular AF in patients with mechanical heart valves or rheumatic mitral stenosis.[3] For cancer-associated VTE, apixaban and rivaroxaban are first-line oral anticoagulants, as they are for AF or VTE in patients with a body mass index over 35 kg/m2 or actual body weight over 120 kg.[3] Regarding safety, the annual risk of intracranial bleeding with a DOAC is approximately half of that with a vitamin K antagonist (VKA) like warfarin.[4] A 2024 retrospective analysis of patients with Stage 4/5 chronic kidney disease and AF showed apixaban was associated with a 47% lower risk of major bleeding versus warfarin, while rivaroxaban was associated with a 65% higher risk of major bleeding compared to warfarin.[5] For patients with AF and valvular heart disease, one retrospective cohort study showed DOAC use was associated with a lower risk for ischemic stroke/systemic embolism and for major bleeding compared to warfarin, while a randomized trial in patients with AF and rheumatic heart disease found a composite outcome was more common with rivaroxaban than warfarin.[5] All DOACs require dose adjustment in people with moderate kidney impairment, and inappropriate dosing is not uncommon, with nearly 60% of reduced-dose DOAC regimens not following FDA recommendations.[3][6] Unlike warfarin, routine laboratory measurement of drug concentrations or relevant coagulation function assays is not required for safe and effective use of DOACs, though it may be beneficial in emergency scenarios.[3]
