.\outputs\codex_findings\full_audit_pass_10\codex_stderr.log:4147:outputs\sweep_r3_final\clinical\clinical_afib_anticoagulation\report.md:5:Most patients with non-valvular atrial fibrillation should receive long-term oral anticoagulation to decrease stroke risk, as the benefit typically outweighs the bleeding risk.[1] Direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs) are first-line agents for stroke prevention in non-valvular atrial fibrillation.[2] For example, standard dosing for apixaban in this indication is 5 mg twice daily, with a reduced dose of 2.5 mg twice daily for patients meeting specific criteria such as age ≥80 years, body weight ≤60 kg, or serum creatinine ≥1.5 mg/dL.[3] Rivaroxaban is dosed at 20 mg daily for atrial fibrillation, with a 15 mg daily dose considered for extended use beyond six months in some contexts.[4] Vitamin K antagonists like warfarin are recommended for patients with mechanical heart valves or valvular atrial fibrillation.[2] Guidelines recommend using stroke risk scores, such as CHA₂DS₂-VASc, for candidate selection, with American Academy of Family Physicians guidelines recommending oral anticoagulants for a CHADS₂ score higher than 1 and allowing for it with a score of 1 in certain circumstances.[2] DOACs do not require routine laboratory monitoring, and for procedures, they can be interrupted without routine bridging therapy; for apixaban 5 mg twice daily, omission for one day before and the day of surgery is recommended for low-to-moderate bleeding risk surgeries.[4] In cases of life-threatening bleeding, specific reversal agents like idarucizumab for dabigatran or andexanet for apixaban and rivaroxaban are recommended.[4][3]
.\outputs\codex_findings\full_audit_pass_10\codex_stderr.log:4148:outputs\sweep_r3_final\clinical\clinical_afib_anticoagulation\report.md:9:Direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs), including apixaban, rivaroxaban, and dabigatran, are first-line for most patients with non-valvular atrial fibrillation (AF) or acute venous thromboembolism (VTE).[5] In contrast, warfarin remains the first-line oral anticoagulant for valvular AF in patients with mechanical heart valves or rheumatic mitral stenosis.[5] For cancer-associated VTE, apixaban and rivaroxaban are considered first-line oral anticoagulants.[5] All DOACs require dose adjustment in people with moderate kidney impairment.[5] Inappropriate dosing of DOACs is not uncommon, with nearly 60% of reduced-dose regimens not following FDA recommendations, which may be associated with increased risk for cardiovascular hospitalization and adverse events like bleeding and all-cause mortality.[6] Underdosing may increase stroke risk while not reducing rates of major bleeding.[6] Specific dosing recommendations vary; for AF, usual doses include apixaban 5mg twice daily, dabigatran 150mg twice daily, edoxaban 60mg daily, and rivaroxaban 20mg daily with food, with specific criteria for reduced doses.[6] Routine laboratory measurement of drug concentrations is not required for safe and effective use of DOACs, though it may be beneficial in emergency scenarios or when excessive or inadequate anticoagulation is suspected.[5]
.\outputs\codex_findings\full_audit_pass_10\codex_stderr.log:4149:outputs\sweep_r3_final\clinical\clinical_afib_anticoagulation\report.md:13:For patients with nonvalvular atrial fibrillation and extreme body weight, defined as a body mass index >40 kg/m² or weight >120 kg, recent guideline updates support the use of direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs).[7] One analysis found rivaroxaban was non-inferior to warfarin in reducing venous thromboembolism recurrence and major bleeding in this population.[7] Consistent with this, individual recommendations now state rivaroxaban and apixaban can be used at standard doses regardless of clinical indication for patients with BMI >40 kg/m² or weight >120 kg.[7] However, the proportion of overweight patients in major DOAC trials was comparatively small relative to the total study populations.[7] For patients with end-stage kidney disease on dialysis, the context is different.[8] The impact of atrial fibrillation on stroke risk in this population is low compared to those without chronic kidney disease, and its association with stroke remains controversial.[8] Some studies report atrial fibrillation increases stroke risk with a hazard ratio of 1.26-1.79, while others from Western countries and Japan find it is not associated with an increased risk in patients on hemodialysis.[8] A Japanese guideline generally does not recommend warfarin for stroke prevention in patients on dialysis, suggesting cautious use with tight INR control may only be considered if stroke risk is estimated to be decreased.[8] In this population, atrial fibrillation is associated with all-cause mortality and cardiovascular events, and its presence may indicate a poor prognosis.[8]
.\outputs\codex_findings\full_audit_pass_10\codex_stderr.log:4150:outputs\sweep_r3_final\clinical\clinical_afib_anticoagulation\report.md:17:The implementation of an electronic clinical decision support (CDS) alert significantly increased the rate of anticoagulation prescription for high-risk ambulatory atrial fibrillation patients not previously on therapy.[9] The alert-based intervention required providers to either prescribe anticoagulation, review guidelines, or document a reason for not prescribing when a high-risk patient without therapy was identified.[9] The trial successfully screened 1670 patients and randomized 798, achieving 100% follow-up data at 90 days for all study participants.[9]
